Germany: a costly fiscal fetish
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is under fierce attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
It was indeed Germany that insisted this principle be included in the criteria set by the Maastricht Treaty, which establishes the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a change in political regime.
Thus, the independence of the Bank of France was one of the strongest arguments in the anti-euro campaign during the Maastricht Treaty ratification referendum in 1992.
In today's Germany, it has become commonplace, one might say, to exert pressure on the central bank.
In recent months, even the Finance Minister, Wolgang Schaüble, has regularly commented on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes central bank independence.
Although he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (this "price stability," in the old jargon of the Bundesbank), he nonetheless offers his advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should handle them to achieve such a goal.
There are precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then Germany's Finance Minister, gave his well-intentioned advice to the first President of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's aim was, in the end, to create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with his typical Dutch brevity, replied that it was nothing unusual for a politician to express his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unheard of). "Yet – he added – it would be entirely abnormal to take [his] suggestions into account."

The respect for monetary policy independence has long been a central element of Germany's Stabilitätkultur («culture of stability»).
The founding act of the reputation for strict independence acquired by the Bundesbank was its refusal to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's requests, who wanted it to contain the rise in interest rates, in 1956.
At that time, France did not see things the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was about to create the Fifth Republic, with a Bank of France that reported to the Minister of Finance.
But it was another time.
Following various crises that shook the Economic and Monetary Union, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Had the old dogma become obsolete?
The Europe remains very vulnerable; the median citizen of the EUM has already lost ten years, and what is even more worrying, we are close to a critical situation.
Yet, the United States are doing better.
Despite a difficult political deadlock to manage, they have managed to tackle the macroeconomic problem (the weakness of aggregate demand) they were facing by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States have also better managed their banking problems, which were initially far more severe than in Europe.
(There is obviously a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
The stronger an economy is, the more profitable its banks are and the more capable they are of fulfilling their function: financing the economy.)
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a Finance Minister than by the lack of public support.
Indeed, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
The exact opposite is true for the ECB.
Voices are being heard, notably in Germany, calling for it to be subjected to more pressure.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's autonomy lies in the unbearable burden that weighs on its shoulders.
The less fiscal policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more central banks are de facto forced to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course, allowing the economy to get stuck in stagnation, or worse).
The political result of this chain of events is a very clear regression toward nationalism, both right and left, in all EU countries, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany leads the dance, with its obsession with the schwarze Null, the budget balance, against all winds and tides.
In Germany, deficits are viewed unfavorably, not only from an arithmetic but also a moral standpoint, even though this defies economic common sense and resembles clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, the main German public finance specialists, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, formulated a "golden rule" according to which current expenditures should, on average, be financed by current revenues.
Public spending, and the resources it requires, are justified by their utility.
This amounts to saying that investments aimed at improving productivity – capital expenditures – can be financed with debt, whose service is ensured by the growth of income and the base of associated revenues.
This conventional approach was institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment expenditures, which is always practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
This is crucial, because in Germany, about 50% of public sector investment expenditures are managed at this level (a proportion that has been declining, since the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with supporting the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (Mittlestand).
But compared to the beginning of the 1990s and at constant prices, investment expenditures have decreased by about 15%.
More than a decade later, they are insufficient to maintain the capital stock.
If this is not how we prepare for the future, this is how we undermine productivity and prosperity.
In short, the schwarze Null goes against the intended goal.
Outdated infrastructure (though not as much as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Furthermore, the fiscal frugality of German leaders spills over beyond German borders, and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which lacks exchange rates to accommodate national peculiarities.
Of course, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But turning the only institution willing to "do what it takes" to bring the EUM back on track into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
Letting states use, where it exists, the budgetary space they have to ease the pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, enjoys some degree of maneuvering room in this regard.
